{{italic title}}
'''''The Empty Space''''' is a 1968 book by the British director [[Peter Brook]] examining four modes or points of view on theatre: Deadly; Holy; Rough; and Immediate. 

The book is based on a series of four lectures endowed by [[Granada Television]] and delivered at Manchester, [[Keele University|Keele]], [[Hull University|Hull]], and [[Sheffield University|Sheffield]] Universities in England. The first lecture, on The Deadly Theatre, was delivered on 1 February 1965 at [[Manchester University]]. The lecture series helped to fund his long-planned trip to Afghanistan.<ref name=Kustow>{{cite book|last1=Kustow|first1=Michael|title=Peter Brook : a biography|date=2006|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]]|location=London|isbn=0-7475-7913-X|page=153}}</ref>

The work was considered controversial when first published in 1968 and received mixed reviews. However, it is now widely taught in higher education theatre studies courses.

''The Empty Space'' is defined by Brook as "[A]ny space in which theatre takes place."  "I can take any empty space and call it a bare stage. A man walks across this empty space whilst someone else is watching him, and this is all that is needed for an act of theatre to be engaged".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brook|first1=Peter|title=The empty space|date=2008|publisher=Penguin|location=London|isbn=0141189223|page=11}}</ref>

'''Empty Space Peter Brook Award'''
[[File:Orange Tree Empty Space Award 2006-1.jpg|thumbnail|[[Sam Walters]] and [[Auriol Smith]] receiving the Empty Space Award for the [[Orange Tree Theatre]] in 2006]]
[[File:Sasha Regan, Union Theatre, London PB040039.jpg|thumbnail|[[Sasha Regan]], [[Union Theatre, London|Union Theatre]], London November 2008]]

The Empty Space Peter Brook Award is an annual prize awarded to a theatre in recognition of pioneering concepts and innovations in theatre achieved in smaller venues and inventive spaces which receive minimal or no public funding. Award categories include regional theatres and up-and-coming theatre. Winners include the [[Orange Tree Theatre]], [[Richmond, London]] (2006 and 2015), [[Unicorn Theatre]], London (2014), the Shed at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]], London (2013), and the [[Finborough Theatre]], London (2012, 2010).

